Exploratory Analysis of Ford GoBike Data¶

by Adam Catney¶

Introduction¶

I will be looking at data for the month of February of 2021 for the Ford GoBike scheme. This is a bike lending scheme in the Bay Area of San Francisco. The data includes length of the trip, when the trips take place, if the users are suscribed members and if they're part of the Bike Share program.

Here I will be conducting an explanatory analysis of the data although first I'll have to clean it up and do some organising.

Cleaning Data¶

Cleaning Summary¶

  • From both a manual look at the .csv file and the Programmatic Assessment there are a few parts of the dataframe that I would like to clean up.
    • Data Types: Currently the start & end time columns are strings, I would like to change this to a datetime format.
    • There are some null and blank entries for, I would like to remove these:
      • 197 for "start_station_id" & "start_station_name" as well as "end_station_id" & "end_station_name"
      • 8265 blanks for "member_birth_year" & "member_gender"
    • There are some columns I definitely don't plan to include in my analysis, I plan to remove the latitude & longitude columns

What is the structure of your original dataset?¶

  • This dataset is made up of bicyle trips from the Ford GoBike program in San Francisco Bay Area.
  • The collected data is for the period of February 2019.
    • NOTE: The provided links for the San Fran bike data from https://github.com/BetaNYC/Bike-Share-Data-Best-Practices/wiki/Bike-Share-Data-Systems#san-francisco-bay-area-ca are not working.
      • http://www.bayareabikeshare.com/
  • The dataset is 183,412 rows long and 16 columns wide.
  • Our data is made up of the following 16 points:
    • duration_sec
    • start_time
    • end_time
    • start_station_id
    • start_station_name
    • start_station_latitude
    • start_station_longitude
    • end_station_id
    • end_station_name
    • end_station_latitude
    • end_station_longitude
    • bike_id
    • user_type
    • member_birth_year
    • member_gender
    • bike_share_for_all_trip
  • Of all the data most of it is "free form" numerical or string entries however a 3 of the columns provide data from a limited selection of options:
    • User Type is made up of "Customer" or "Subscriber".
    • Member Gender is made up of "Male", "Female", "Other" or blank. Given the nature of the question this could simple be a customer preferring not to say.
    • Bike Share For All Trip is made up of "Yes" or "No".

What changes did we see to dataset after cleaning?¶

  • Our data is now deceased to 174,951 rows
  • We only have 11 columns now having dropped the 4 associated with latitude & longtitude.
  • The time columns have been changed to datetime format.
  • The user type column has been converted to category data type

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

While I am interested in exploring the dataframe more to see which points will reveal the most useful conclusions for an analysis. However I am most curious about which data might help us estimate the most demanding times throughout the month for bikes and what sort of customers tend to use the bikes from this scheme.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • start_time should show us when bikes are most in demand.
  • user_type, member_birth_year & member_gender may allow us to see the types of participants in the scheme.
  • duration_sec could show us how long these bike trips typically last.

Univariate Exploration¶

The points that we will be exploring through this part of the analysis is:

  • Bike trips by:
    • Hour of Day
    • Day of Month
    • Weekday
      • Members by Gender
      • Members by Type
      • Members by Year of Birth/Age
      • Length of Trips

The above 3 sets of visualisations is a transformation effort using scale transforamtions by applying a logarithmic transformation to the data.

This gives us a useful visual as this dataset has some odd outliers in the data.

  • Max trip duration in minutes = 1409.133333
  • Meanwhile the mean was only = 11.7

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • I applied a transformation to the trip duration as there where some oddities with the maximum values. This can be seen as the max trip duration was 1409.13 minutes which is only just over 1/2 hour less than a full day (24 hours).
  • Applying the log scale transformation to the trip duration (in minutes) shows us a normal distribution curve, peaking at 10 minutes, which is far more useful visual.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • I broke the start_time down into additional columns for:
    • Hour of the Day
    • Day of the Month
    • Weekday
  • Due to the unyieldy nature of using timings in seconds I transformed these figures into minutes which made them more manageable.
  • For the Date of Births I found there were some odd years stretching back as far as 1878, I discared any dates further back than 1920.
    • Although it's still unlikely 100 year olds where regularly using the bike system I decided to remain cautious with my cut off date.

Some Overall Conclusions¶

Subscribers vs Customers¶

Most of those who take part in the scheme are Subscribers with the Customers making up less than 10% of them. Overall there are also far more men than women taking part in the scheme. When looking more closely at this we also see men make up majority for both Subscribers & Customers. However despite this large disparity in volume we also see that proportionately both genders tend to be subscribers by about the same amount. Male members, in particular subscribers, are the oldest group while females have the lowest median age. Males across both user types have the broadest range between their 1st and 3rd quartile.

Consumers tend to take longer trips which seems to indicate that while Subscribers use the bikes for day to day commuting while consumers are using them for more ad hoc needs, likely including leisure or perhaps even visitors to the City.

Trips throughout the Day & Month¶

Day-to-Day the Customers don't tend to see much variance throughout the week. Meanwhile Subscribers use the bikes for trips mostly throughout the weeks with a significant drop-off during the weekend.

Throughout the month we see peaks and troughs however most of the drop-offs seem to coincide with the weekend which aligns with what we saw elsewhere. There are some other days where trips aren't common but we don't have enough data to say how, these could simply be days when the weather is too poor for going out on the bike.

Gender appears to be insignificant when it comes to Male & Female members throughout the weekday and month day data, with them sharing the same peaks and troughs but with Males being obviously more numerous due to the earlier mentioned difference in membership between the two genders.

The busiest time of day is around 08:00, likely when people are commutting to work or school, with the slowest time being in the early AM around 02:00 which makes a lot of logical sense.

Ages of Users¶

The most significant group of members are those who where born in the latter half of the 80's to the mid-90's. Men, on average, tended to be older with the Male Subscribers having the oldest members.

We also see that the majority of trips are undertaken by members in their 20's & 30's with the overall mean age of members being 34.

The elderly members tend to go on shorter trips.

Bike Share For All Program¶

The Bike Share Program is in the majority when it comes to users with only 9.9% of trips being part of this scheme. We also see that there are 0 Customers that take part of this scheme which may indicate that it is not open to non-Subscribers.
